    <item>
      <title>Show HN: lambda-nat-proxy – Serverless proxy using Lambda and UDP NAT punching</title>
      <link>https://github.com/dan-v/lambda-nat-proxy</link>
      <description>Revisited an old experiment of mine (&lt;a href=&quot;https:&amp;#x2F;&amp;#x2F;github.com&amp;#x2F;dan-v&amp;#x2F;awslambdaproxy&quot;&gt;https:&amp;#x2F;&amp;#x2F;github.com&amp;#x2F;dan-v&amp;#x2F;awslambdaproxy&lt;/a&gt;): can AWS Lambda functions work as network proxies? This time using UDP NAT hole punching + QUIC tunnels.&lt;p&gt;Client discovers public IP via STUN, writes session data to S3, which triggers a Lambda. Both endpoints punch UDP holes through their NATs, then establish a QUIC connection for encrypted traffic forwarding.</description>
